In [[music]], '''flat''' or '''bemolle''' (Italian: "soft B") means "lower in [[pitch (music)|pitch]]". More specifically, in [[musical notation]], flat means "lower in [[Pitch (music)|pitch]] by one [[semitone]] (half step)". Flat is the opposite of [[Sharp (music)|sharp]], which is a raising of pitch.

In [[music notation]], the flat symbol, {{Music|b}}, derived from a stylised lowercase "''b''", lowers a [[Musical note|note]] by a [[semitone|half step]] (semitone).<ref>Benward & Saker (2003). ''Music in Theory and Practice, Vol. 1'', p. 6. McGraw-Hill, Seventh edition. "''Flat'' ({{music|b}})—lowers the pitch a half step."</ref><ref>[http://www.naxos.com/mainsite/NewDesign/fglossary.files/bglossary.files/Flat.htm Flat], [http://www.naxos.com/education/glossary.asp Glossary], [[Naxos Records]]</ref> For instance, the music below has a key signature with three flats (indicating either [[E-flat major|E{{Music|b}} major]] or [[C minor]]) and the note, [[D♭ (musical note)|D{{Music|b}}]], has a flat [[Accidental (music)|accidental]].

: <score lang="lilypond"> {
\override Score.TimeSignature #'stencil = ##f
\relative c'' { 

  \clef treble \key es \major \time 4/4 des1
} }

</score>
The [[Unicode]] character ♭ (U+266D) can be found in the [[Plane (Unicode)|block]] [[Miscellaneous Symbols]]; its [[HTML entity]] is <tt>&amp;#9837;</tt>.

Under [[twelve-tone equal temperament]], [[C-flat (musical note)|C{{music|b}}]] for instance is the same as (or [[enharmonically equivalent]] to) [[B (musical note)|B{{music|natural}}]], and [[G-flat (musical note)|G{{music|b}}]] is equivalent to [[F♯ (musical note)|F{{Music|#}}]]. In any other [[Musical tuning#Tuning systems|tuning system]], such enharmonic equivalences in general do not exist. To allow extended [[just intonation]], composer [[Ben Johnston (composer)|Ben Johnston]] uses a sharp as an accidental to indicate a note is raised 70.6 [[cent (music)|cents]] (ratio 25:24), and a flat to indicate a note is lowered 70.6 cents.<ref>[[John Fonville]]. "Ben Johnston's Extended Just Intonation- A Guide for Interpreters", p. 109, ''Perspectives of New Music'', Vol. 29, No. 2 (Summer, 1991), pp. 106–137. "...the [[Just chromatic semitone|25/24 ratio]] is the sharp ({{music|#}}) ratio...this raises a note approximately 70.6 cents."</ref>

In [[Intonation (music)|intonation]], flat can also mean "slightly lower in pitch" (by some unspecified amount). If two simultaneous notes are slightly out-of-tune, the lower-pitched one (assuming the higher one is properly pitched) is "flat" with respect to the other. Furthermore, the verb ''flatten'' means to lower the pitch of a note, typically by a [[Comma (music)|small musical interval]].

== Key signatures ==
Flats are used in the [[key signature]]s of
* [[F major]] / [[D minor]]
* [[B-flat major|B{{music|b}} major]] / [[G minor]]
* [[E-flat major|E{{music|b}} major]] / [[C minor]]
* [[A-flat major|A{{music|b}} major]] / [[F minor]]
* [[D-flat major|D{{music|b}} major]] / [[B-flat minor|B{{music|b}} minor]]
* [[G-flat major|G{{music|b}} major]] / [[E-flat minor|E{{music|b}} minor]]
* [[C-flat major|C{{music|b}} major]] / [[A-flat minor|A{{music|b}} minor]]
The order of flats in the key signatures of music notation, following the [[circle of fifths]], is B{{music|b}}, E{{music|b}}, A{{music|b}}, D{{music|b}}, G{{music|b}}, C{{music|b}} and F{{music|b}} ([[mnemonic|mnemonics]] for which include '''B'''attle '''E'''nds '''A'''nd '''D'''own '''G'''oes '''C'''harles' '''F'''ather ''and'' '''B'''efore '''E'''ating '''A''' '''D'''oughnut '''G'''et '''C'''offee '''F'''irst).

== Related symbols ==
'''Double flats''' also exist, which look like {{music|bb}} (similar to two flats, {{music|b}}{{music|b}}) and lower a note by two semitones, or a whole step. The Unicode character 𝄫 (U+1D12B) in the [[Musical Symbols (Unicode block)|Musical Symbols]] block represents the double-flat sign.

: <score vorbis="1"> {
\override Score.TimeSignature #'stencil = ##f
\relative c'' { 

  \clef treble \key c \major \time 4/4 beses1
} }

</score>
A '''quarter-tone flat''' or '''half flat''', indicating the use of [[quarter tone]]s, may be marked with various symbols including a flat with a slash ({{music|flatstroke}}) or a reversed flat sign ({{music|d}}). A '''three-quarter-tone flat''', '''flat and a half''' or '''sesquiflat''', is represented by a half flat and a regular flat ({{music|db}}).

: <score vorbis="1"> {
\override Score.TimeSignature #'stencil = ##f
\relative c'' { 

  \clef treble \key c \major \time 4/4 ceh1 deseh
} }</score>
Although very uncommon, a '''triple flat''' ({{music|bbb}}) can sometimes be found.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informatics.indiana.edu/donbyrd/CMNExtremes.htm|title=Extremes of Conventional Music Notation|last=Byrd|first=Donald|date=September 2016|publisher=[[Indiana University Bloomington]]|access-date=4 November 2016}}</ref> It lowers a note three [[semitone]]s.

