{{Infobox organization |name = Harvard–Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics |image = Center for Astrophysics.jpg |caption = Exterior view of the CfA. |established = 1973 |mission = To advance knowledge and understanding of the universe through research and education in astronomy and astrophysics |leader_title = Director |leader_name = [[Charles R. Alcock]] |location = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]] |headquarters = 60 Garden Street |website = [http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/ Official website] }} The '''Harvard–Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics''' ('''CfA''') is a research institute which carries out a broad program of research in [[astronomy]], [[astrophysics]], [[earth science|earth]] and [[space science]]s, and [[science education]]. The center's mission is to advance knowledge and understanding of the [[universe]] through research and education in astronomy and astrophysics.
The center was founded in 1973 as a joint venture between the [[Smithsonian Institution]] and [[Harvard University]]. It consists of the [[Harvard College Observatory]] and the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]]. The center's main facility is located between Concord Avenue and Garden Street, with its mailing address and main entrance at 60 Garden Street, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. Beyond this location there are also additional satellite facilities elsewhere around the globe. The current director of the CfA, [[Charles R. Alcock]], was named in 2004.<ref> {{cite news| url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2004/05.20/01-alcock.html |title=Alcock to lead the CfA: Astrophysicist noted for 'dark matter' studies to take helm at observatories |publisher=Harvard Gazette |date=2004-05-20 |accessdate=2007-12-25 }}</ref> The director from 1982 to 2004 was [[Irwin I. Shapiro]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/1998/10.15/Harvard-Smithso.html| title=Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics Celebrates 25 Years |publisher=Harvard University Gazette |date=1998-10-15 |accessdate=2007-02-26 }}</ref>
